[[File:U. Dist. Street Fair 2007 corn.jpg|thumb|A corn roaster being used at a street fair in Seattle, Washington]] [[File:LafSquareCornRoaster.JPG|thumb|A commercial corn roaster]] [[File:A commercial corn roaster.jpg|thumb|A smaller commercial corn roaster]]
A '''corn roaster''' is a large [[Grill (cooking)|grill]] for cooking large batches of ears of [[Maize|corn]] at the same time. The term "corn roaster" can also refer to a person who roasts corn.<ref>Lempert, Phil (2002). [https://books.google.com/books?id=I4zIScjNnE4C&pg=PA141 ''Being the Shopper: Understanding the Buyer's Choice'']. John Wiley & Sons. p. 141. {{ISBN|0471263737}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/photo-contest/2011/entries/113696/view/ | title=The Corn Roaster | publisher=''[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]'' | accessdate=29 August 2014 | author=2014}}</ref><ref name="Barnard">{{cite web | url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/artslife/1155840-at-the-galleries-pointed-playful-and-political | title=At The Galleries: Pointed, playful and political | publisher=''The Chronicle Herald'' | date=September 21, 2013 | accessdate=29 August 2014 | author=Barnard, Elissa}}</ref> Corn roaster machines have existed in the United States since at least 1900.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mAvRAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA713 ''Annual Report of the Commissioner of Patents for the Year'']. United States Patent Office. 1900. p. 713.</ref> Corn roasters are used by [[Concession stand|concession vendors]] at [[festival]]s, [[fair]]s, events, parties and holidays, such as the Fourth of July in the United States.<ref name="Nyhus"/><ref name="Eichman"/> Roasted corn is a very popular festival food in the American South, Southwest and Northwest. Corn roasters can also cook foods such as [[turkey meat|turkey]] legs [[potato]]es and [[sweet potato]]es. They may also be used by [[street food]] vendors.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.seattleweekly.com/voracious/2008/05/corn_roasters_are_all_over_the.php | title=Corn Roasters Are All Over the Place | publisher=''[[Seattle Weekly]]'' | date=May 29, 2008 | accessdate=29 August 2014 | author=Kauffman, Jonathan}}</ref><ref name="TTN">{{cite web | url=http://www.taosnews.com/news/business/article_2664ff84-0b74-11e3-af06-0019bb2963f4.html | title=For Taos man, corn is the crop | publisher=''[[The Taos News]]'' | date=August 23, 2013 | accessdate=29 August 2014 | author=Cleary, Elizabeth}}</ref> Street vendors may operate seasonally, per the seasonality of corn crops.<ref name="TTN"/> Some organizations that operate corn roasters at events, such as fairs, donate their proceeds to charities.<ref name="DSN">{{cite web | url=http://www.dailysunnews.com/news/2009/jul/28/shake-up-on-yakima-valley-fair-board/ | title=Shake-up on Yakima Valley Fair board | publisher=''Daily Sun News'' | date=July 28, 2009 | accessdate=29 August 2014}}</ref>
Many commercial corn roasters come mounted on a [[trailer (vehicle)|trailer]]. The corn roasters use [[Liquefied petroleum gas|LPG]] for fuel. Smaller versions exist, such as rotary corn roasters that can be placed on a table,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ap-magazine.com/foodmachinery-product/Detail_92363_Rotary-Corn-Roaster-EB-18-2.html | title=Rotary Corn Roaster | publisher=Asia-Pacific Magazine | date=2011 | accessdate=29 August 2014}}</ref> and some corn roasters are homemade.<ref name="Barnard"/><ref name="Eichman">{{cite web | url=http://www.heraldargus.com/news/local/a-family-thing/article_2c9cc2fb-344d-503b-914d-d33a64748caf.html | title='A family thing' | publisher=''Herald Argus'' | date=June 20, 2011 | accessdate=29 August 2014 | author=Eichman, Brianne}}</ref><ref>Fitzgerald, Barb (contributor), (2006). [https://books.google.com/books?id=RAnr797nEFkC&pg=PA110 ''Food Booth: The Complete Guide to Starting and Operating a Food Concession Business'']. Carnival Press. p. 110. {{ISBN|0976570319}}</ref>
==Manufacturers== There are several different manufactures who make corn roasters in the [[United States]]. A company that produces corn roasters is Holstein Manufacturing.<ref>Brown, Douglas Robert (2007). [https://books.google.com/books?id=uN1V-O0Xq54C&pg=PT568 ''The Restaurant Manager's Handbook'']. Atlantic Publishing Company. {{ISBN|0910627975}}</ref> A brand of corn roaster is named "Roast-O-Matic".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qTlDAAAAYAAJ&q=%22Corn+roaster%22&dq=%22Corn+roaster%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xkMBVMTYBqLTiwLK94EY&ved=0CFEQ6AEwBjgK ''Rural Enterprise, Volumes 1-6'']. 1986. p. v.</ref> Some corn roasters can roast up to 1,200 ears of corn per hour.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://fruitgrowersnews.com/index.php/magazine/article/Pennsylvania-Farm-Specializes-in-Adding-Value | title=Pennsylvania Farm Specializes in Adding Value | publisher=Fruit Growers News | date=April 7, 2007 | accessdate=29 August 2014}}</ref>
==Use at events== At the annual [[Minnesota State Fair]] in [[Falcon Heights, Minnesota]], a group of up to 50 to 55 personnel produces significant quantities of roasted corn, which can vary daily.<ref name="Nyhus"/> This variance can range between 10,000 and 18,000 ears of roasted corn a day.<ref name="Nyhus"/> Approximately 180,000 ears of roasted corn are produced for the duration of the fair.<ref name="Nyhus"/> Roasted corn at the Minnesota State Fair has been described as "one of the fair’s most popular foods for more than 28 years".<ref name="Nyhus"/> At the Yakima Valley Fair in [[Yakima, Washington]], the Grandview Rotary Club has been operating a corn roaster for 40 years, and donates the proceeds to various local needs.<ref name="DSN"/>
